From: Meerzulee <mirzaali@screeninternational.org>
Date: 2026-05-13
Subject: [PATCH] ps4_mts: v95 — fix v94 carrier race with ndo_open

v94 boot showed the fix DOES fire correctly:
  ps4_mts: v94: netif_carrier_on (PHY-level: BMSR=0x7969 LPA=0xcde1)
But the kthread sets carrier_on at ~6s, then ndo_open at ~27s reads
linkreg bit 0 (still 0 since MAC bit 0 doesn't latch on v93+ rings)
and calls netif_carrier_off, OVERWRITING the kthread's setting.

The kthread's `last_phy_carrier` cache also stayed true so it didn't
re-fire when carrier got cleared — resulting in permanent carrier=0,
ip refusing to xmit, ping dropped.

v95 fixes both sides:
1. Kthread: compare phy_carrier against `netif_carrier_ok(ndev)`
   instead of the internal cache.  If anything externally clears
   carrier (ndo_open's blind off, ip toggling), kthread re-asserts
   on next 3s tick.
2. ndo_open: drop the unconditional `netif_carrier_off` else branch.
   Let kthread own the PHY-derived state.  ndo_open still does
   netif_carrier_on if MAC bit 0 happens to be latched.

Signed-off-by: Meerzulee <mirzaali@screeninternational.org>
Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.7 (1M context) <noreply@anthropic.com>
---
--- a/drivers/net/ethernet/sony/ps4_mts.c
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/sony/ps4_mts.c
@@ -1172,24 +1172,32 @@
 			u16 v_bmsr = 0xffff, v_lpa = 0xffff;
 			bool phy_carrier;
 
-			if (mts_smi_c22_read(mts, 0x01, &v_bmsr) == 0 &&
+			if (mts->ndev &&
+			    mts_smi_c22_read(mts, 0x01, &v_bmsr) == 0 &&
 			    mts_smi_c22_read(mts, 0x05, &v_lpa) == 0) {
 				phy_carrier = (v_bmsr & 0x0020) &&
 					      (v_lpa & 0x4000);
-				if (mts->ndev && phy_carrier != mts->last_phy_carrier) {
+				/* v95: compare against the actual netdev carrier
+				 * state instead of an internal cache.  Reason:
+				 * ndo_open in v93 unconditionally calls
+				 * netif_carrier_off when linkreg bit 0 is 0,
+				 * which would overwrite an already-set carrier.
+				 * Using netif_carrier_ok() lets us detect that
+				 * override and re-assert on the next tick. */
+				if (phy_carrier != netif_carrier_ok(mts->ndev)) {
 					if (phy_carrier) {
 						netif_carrier_on(mts->ndev);
 						dev_info(&mts->pdev->dev,
-							 "v94: netif_carrier_on (PHY-level: BMSR=0x%04x LPA=0x%04x)\n",
+							 "v94/v95: netif_carrier_on (PHY-level: BMSR=0x%04x LPA=0x%04x)\n",
 							 v_bmsr, v_lpa);
 					} else {
 						netif_carrier_off(mts->ndev);
 						dev_info(&mts->pdev->dev,
-							 "v94: netif_carrier_off (BMSR=0x%04x LPA=0x%04x)\n",
+							 "v94/v95: netif_carrier_off (BMSR=0x%04x LPA=0x%04x)\n",
 							 v_bmsr, v_lpa);
 					}
-					mts->last_phy_carrier = phy_carrier;
 				}
+				mts->last_phy_carrier = phy_carrier;
 			}
 		}
 
@@ -1336,10 +1344,12 @@
 		 "v93: ndo_open %s tx_ring=%pad rx_ring=%pad\n",
 		 ndev->name, &mts->tx_ring_dma, &mts->rx_ring_dma);
 
+	/* v95: only set carrier_on here if the MAC has actually latched
+	 * link bit 0.  Do NOT call netif_carrier_off — the phy_ctrl
+	 * kthread owns the PHY-derived carrier state (see v94), and
+	 * unconditionally clearing it here races with the kthread cache. */
 	if (readl(mts->bar + MTS_LINK_STATUS) & 0x1)
 		netif_carrier_on(ndev);
-	else
-		netif_carrier_off(ndev);
 	return 0;
 }
 
